–1169":"1104–1169","1081–1150":"1081–1150","1070–Female":"1070–Deceased","1106–1141":"1106–1141","1108–Male":"1108–Deceased","1057–1129":"1057–1129","1058–Female":"1058–Deceased","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1081":"1081","1070":"1070","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","Bef 1130":"before 1130","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","about 1108":"about 1108","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","about 1065":"about 1065","1108":"1108","Condé-en-Brie, Aisne, Picardie, Frankrijk":"Condé-en-Brie, Aisne, Picardie, France","Thorngate Castle, Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cundy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon, of Norman origin): habitational name from any of several places in Normandy and Picardy called Condé, a French form of the Gaulish <i>condate</i> ‘junction of rivers’. Members of the de Condé family held land in Lincolnshire, Kent, Leicestershire, Cambridgeshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th century. The strong presence of the surname in 16th-century Cornwall and Devon is unexpected, but is probably the result of migration from counties further east or north. Derivation from the Cornish language is implausible, and there is no known place in Cornwall which could have given rise to it as a habitational name."],"variants":[{"name":"Condict","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brigid, Fergus, Liam.","English (Cornwall): hypercorrected form of <b>Condit(t)</b> and <b>Cundit(t)</b>, from Middle English <i>conduit, condit, cundit</i>, originally an artificial channel or pipe for conveying water, later a fountain or pump (the surname probably refers to the latter). The surname may sometimes have been confused with   Cundy  . See also   Condit  .","Irish: variant of   Connick  , a patronymic from Gaelic <b>Mac Conmhaic</b>."]},{"name":"Condy","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall, of Norman origin): variant of   Cundy  . Compare   Candee  .","French (southern): unexplained."]}]},{"name":"Osbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It is not now common, but in the earlier 20th century it enjoyed a modest vogue in Britain, being borne for example by the cartoonist  Osbert Lancaster  (  1908–86 ) and the writer  Osbert Sitwell  (  1892–1969 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":1,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":21,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":31,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":41,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Osbert de Cundy was born about 1065, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Osbert de Condé, was 9 and his mother, Mrs. Osbert de Conde, was 8. He had at least 3 sons with Adelaide Chesney. He died before 1130, in Lincoln, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, and was buried in Condé-en-Brie, Aisne, Picardie, France."},"et":{"about 1065–Bef 1130":"umbes 1065–enne 1130","1065–1130":"1065–1130","1104–1169":"1104–1169","1081–1150":"1081–1150","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","1106–1141":"1106–1141","1108–Male":"1108–Surnud","1057–1129":"1057–1129","1058–Female":"1058–Surnud","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1086":"1086","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1150":"1150","1081":"1081","1070":"1070","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","Bef 1130":"enne 1130","1104":"1104","1169":"1169","about 1108":"umbes 1108","1058":"1058","1057":"1057","about 1065":"umbes 1065","1108":"1108","